@simo5 FWIW, the implementation that I released has been extracted from the [acme.jose](https://github.com/certbot/certbot/tree/232f5a92d193b1b4a955d0d5f2d1ea639215331d/acme/acme/jose) package by the letsencrypt folks and is not a new one. Why they chose to write their own I'm not sure (maybe @bmw knows?) but while researching a library I've found no clear statement that jwcrypto has a higher chance of long term maintenance. I'm happy to be wrong though, since I totally agree that there should be only one library based on cryptography that implements JOSE. It makes sense to me that having fewer libraries implementing JOSE reduces the chance of having an unfixed vulnerability again.

@alex Have you considered blessing one of the existing JOSE libraries and move it into the PyCA organization, making it the de facto standard implementation?

@bmw @erikrose Have you considered *dropping* your JOSE implementation in favor of one that is equally or better maintained than `acme.jose`?

@tiran @simo5 Do you consider jwcrypto to be secure in terms of long term maintenance?

