@sonytricoire  Are these resources created in another CloudFormation stack or were these resources created outside of CloudFormation. 

If they are in a different stack, you can export the Lambda functions and use Fn::ImportValue.

If they were created outside of CloudFormation, there isn't much we can currently do unfortunately. This is a limitation on CloudFormation in general, since they do not allow customers to control existing resources through a CloudFormation Stack. Since SAM is built on top of this, we have to wait for CloudFormation to add this capability.

Just a note to self here on an idea that occurred to me today. If we made document part XML parsing "lazy", meaning the XML wasn't parsed until the first time the XML element was accessed, that would allow the XML in the document to contain whatever kinds of template markup was desired, including `for loops` and all that sort of thing typical in an HTML templating environment. This would only work for "curated" templates, but could be a very powerful solution for developers willing to template directly in the WordprocessingML.

It also occurs to me that there may be no compelling reason to keep the template in the document "package". It could be maintained as a separate application resource, like those for a web application are, and the XML product produced by rendering the template written into the document (or whatever) part blob.

