For now I'm using `meta` to store only/exclude, and use them in a doc-generating project to shorten the `example outputs` of my endpoints.
```
"user": {
  "$ref": "#/definitions/User",
  "meta": {
    "only": [
      "id",
      "email",
      "name"
    ]
  }
}
```

A first fix could be to include those in the `meta` by default, to just make it available for client-side usage (without needing a duplicate declaration in the field's declaration).
```
user = fields.Nested(UserSchema, only=['id', 'email', 'name'], meta={
  'only': ['id', 'email', 'name']
})
```

As said by jmcarp, the OpenAPI spec doesn't allow such things at this time, so for now the only solutions are at least not supported, at most incompatible with the spec. Though, they're still required by most.

This approach (using `meta`) wouldn't break compatibility with other doc-reader, just allow us client developers to use the data.

If you guys accept it, I can do a PR 👍

